R</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH044000%2F1"><gtr:id>D0809BDC-EEB1-4E34-A48D-A1FA7C1DE2B2</gtr:id><gtr:title>Translating technical solutions into socio-technical possibilities: enabling technological transfer in the Bangladesh shipbreaking industry</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H044000/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Ship breaking on the beaches of South Asia, and particularly Bangladesh, is one of the most controversial of global recycling activiites. The controversies concern two issues: labour conditions in the breaking yards and environmental containment. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>One policy response has been to rekindle the ship breaking industry in those parts of the world where it has long been moribund (eg the EU). A second has been to begin to explore the potential for technology transfer as a means to improved environmental containment and enhanced labour conditions. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project takes the second response further. It takes a partnership approach to move identified transitional technical solutions further toward their potential uptake by market. A two-stage workshop is the principle means to progressing this aim. The workshops aim to:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Identify lessons learned from other transitional technological transfer projects in the sector.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To draw on these lessons, and from research conducted under The Waste of the World programme, to discuss the solutions identified within recent DEFRA-funded research, and to identify which solutions are socially as well as technically possible.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To enable and facilitate active discussion of these possibilities in Bangladesh. &lt;br />&lt;/li>
